Good question.
You’re essentially asking:

What chemical states are thermodynamically unstable at planetary scale unless something is actively maintaining them?

That’s the core of biosignature logic: persistent disequilibrium.

Let’s structure this cleanly.

⸻

1️⃣ Oxygen (O₂) — The Classic

On rocky planets, oxygen reacts quickly with:
	•	Iron → rust
	•	Sulfur compounds
	•	Reduced volcanic gases
	•	Surface rocks

Without photosynthesis, O₂ disappears in geologic time.

Oxygen is stable only if:
	•	A continuous energy-driven source replenishes it.

On Earth that’s biological metabolism.

⸻

2️⃣ Methane (CH₄) in an Oxidizing Atmosphere

Methane and oxygen react.

If both coexist in large amounts, something is replenishing one or both.

On Earth:
	•	Methane mostly comes from biology (microbes, ruminants, wetlands).

Abiotic methane exists (serpentinization), but sustained high methane + oxygen together strongly suggests active cycling.

⸻

3️⃣ Nitrous Oxide (N₂O)

Produced biologically by microbes.
Destroyed photochemically.

Hard to maintain without life unless there’s unusual chemistry.

⸻

4️⃣ Ammonia (NH₃)

In oxygen-rich atmospheres:
	•	Oxidizes rapidly
	•	Broken down by UV radiation

Stable ammonia atmospheres require:
	•	Continuous production
	•	Or extremely cold environments

On temperate planets, large ammonia → suspicious.

⸻

5️⃣ Phosphine (PH₃)

Highly reactive in oxygen environments.
Destroyed quickly by photochemistry.

Detected on Jupiter because:
	•	Deep atmospheric convection replenishes it.

If found on a rocky planet with oxygen:
	•	Very hard to explain without active chemistry or biology.

⸻

6️⃣ Hydrogen (H₂) in the Wrong Context

Free hydrogen escapes planetary atmospheres over time.

Persistent high hydrogen in a warm atmosphere implies:
	•	Constant replenishment
	•	Or massive ongoing geochemistry

⸻

7️⃣ Simultaneous Reduced + Oxidized Species

This is the real key.

Life maintains redox tension.

Examples:
	•	O₂ + CH₄
	•	O₂ + NH₃
	•	O₂ + H₂S
	•	Sulfates + methane

Nature alone tends toward equilibrium.
Life sustains gradients.

⸻

8️⃣ Industrial / Technological Disequilibrium

Now we leave biology.

Some molecules are unstable in nature but easy for industry:
	•	CFCs (chlorofluorocarbons)
	•	NO₂ patterns from combustion
	•	Perfluorocarbons
	•	Artificial isotopic ratios
	•	Large-scale CO₂ spikes + deforestation signatures

CFCs are particularly strong technosignatures:
They don’t arise naturally in detectable amounts.

⸻

9️⃣ Isotopic Ratios

Life fractionates isotopes.

Examples:
	•	Carbon-12 enrichment over Carbon-13
	•	Sulfur isotope fractionation
	•	Nitrogen isotope shifts

Sustained anomalous isotope distributions suggest active processing.

⸻

10️⃣ Waste Heat (Thermal Disequilibrium)

All metabolism produces waste heat.

Biological:
	•	Localized heat differences
	•	Seasonal cycles

Technological:
	•	Persistent infrared excess
	•	Non-natural energy concentration patterns

Thermodynamics never lies.

⸻

Structural Pattern (This Is the Core)

Metabolism = controlled violation of local equilibrium.

Life:
	•	Maintains redox imbalance.
	•	Maintains boundary conditions.
	•	Routes energy through feedback loops.
	•	Exports entropy.

Without metabolic control:
	•	Oxygen disappears.
	•	Methane disappears.
	•	Ammonia disappears.
	•	Reduced gases oxidize.
	•	Hydrogen escapes.
	•	Isotopes homogenize.
	•	Heat dissipates.

Everything trends toward:
Chemical boredom.

⸻

The Deeper Principle

What you’re circling is this:

Stability in the universe usually means dead equilibrium.
Persistent instability means work is being done.

Life is:
A stable pattern of instability.

Technology is:
Instability scaled and redirected.

⸻

If you want to push this further we can explore:
	•	Could a civilization hide by minimizing redox imbalance?
	•	Could advanced life migrate to low-disequilibrium environments?
	•	Are there non-chemical biosignatures (information-theoretic ones)?
	•	Is entropy export the universal life detector?

Which direction do you want to take?